# jax-metal-prototype

Running **JAX matmul on the Apple GPU** through hand-written Metal — a from-scratch,
learning-focused prototype that grows toward a real JAX backend for Apple Silicon.

It ships three matmul backends behind one JAX-friendly API, and two ways to call them
natively from JAX:

```python
import jaxmetal
c = jaxmetal.matmul(a, b, device="mps")   # "mps" | "metal" | "cpu" | "auto"
```

```python
import jaxmetal.ffi as jf                 # runs INSIDE jax.jit (XLA FFI custom call)

@jax.jit
def model(a, b):
    c = jf.matmul(a, b)                   # Metal (MPS) matmul as a native custom call
    return jnp.tanh(c) + 1.0             # composes with normal JAX ops
```

Everything is bit-exact against `jnp.matmul`.

---

## The headline finding

> On an Apple M4 Pro, for **f32 matmul**, the GPU only beats the CPU when operands are
> **resident on the GPU** — because Apple's CPU BLAS (Accelerate/AMX) is *very* strong,
> and per-call host↔GPU copies otherwise erase the GPU's advantage.

Compute-only GFLOP/s (GPU-resident operands), measured by `examples/03_resident_speed.py`:

| N | MPS (GPU) | our hand kernel | Accelerate (CPU) | MPS / CPU |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| 512 | 557 | 1043 | 1409 | 0.40× |
| 1024 | 1472 | 1786 | 3091 | 0.48× |
| 2048 | 5106 | 2176 | 3212 | **1.59×** |
| 4096 | 5484 | 2171 | 3130 | **1.75×** |

Three takeaways, all in the code and docs:

1. **MPS beats the CPU from N≈2048 (1.5–1.8×)** — but only for resident operands. This
   is exactly why PyTorch/JAX keep tensors on-device instead of auto-routing per op, and
   why the endgame is a real device (the PJRT plugin), not a per-call wrapper.
2. **Apple's `MPSMatrixMultiplication` (~5.5 TFLOP/s) is what PyTorch MPS uses** and is
   ~2.5× our hand-written kernel — Apple GPUs have no f32 matrix unit, so the win is pure
   microarchitecture tuning (optimal tiling, double-buffering) we don't fully replicate.
3. **Our hand kernel reaches ~2.2 TFLOP/s** from scratch; the big levers were
   occupancy-aware register blocking (4×4 micro-tiles; 8×8 over-spilled and was *slower*)
   and `float4` vectorization. See `kernels/matmul.metal`.

---

## Quickstart

Requirements: macOS on Apple Silicon, Xcode Command Line Tools, Homebrew.

```bash
# 1. Build tools + a JAX-compatible Python env (system Python is too new for jaxlib)
brew install cmake ninja
uv venv --python 3.12 .venv
uv pip install --python .venv numpy "jax[cpu]"

# 2. Build the native library (with the XLA FFI handler enabled)
cmake -S . -B build -G Ninja \
  -DJAX_FFI_INCLUDE_DIR=$(.venv/bin/python -c "import jax.ffi; print(jax.ffi.include_dir())")
cmake --build build          # -> build/libmetal_capi.dylib

# 3. Run the examples
.venv/bin/python examples/01_backends_and_batching.py
.venv/bin/python examples/02_jit_ffi.py
.venv/bin/python examples/03_resident_speed.py

# 4. Tests
ctest --test-dir build --output-on-failure     # 33 C++ unit tests (kernels + runtime)
.venv/bin/python python/test_jaxmetal.py        # jaxmetal vs jnp.matmul, all shapes
```

---

## Examples

| file | shows |
|---|---|
| [`examples/01_backends_and_batching.py`](examples/01_backends_and_batching.py) | `jaxmetal.matmul(device=...)` on each backend; full `jnp.matmul` batching/broadcast |
| [`examples/02_jit_ffi.py`](examples/02_jit_ffi.py) | Metal matmul running **inside `jax.jit`** via an XLA FFI custom call |
| [`examples/03_resident_speed.py`](examples/03_resident_speed.py) | the GPU-vs-CPU crossover (MPS resident vs Accelerate) |

### 1. Backends + batching

```python
import jaxmetal
jaxmetal.matmul(a, b, device="mps")     # Apple's MPS kernel (fastest GPU path)
jaxmetal.matmul(a, b, device="metal")   # our from-scratch MSL kernel
jaxmetal.matmul(a, b, device="cpu")     # Accelerate/BLAS
jaxmetal.matmul(a, b, device="auto")    # size-based router (default)

jaxmetal.matmul(x4d, y3d)               # batched + broadcasting, like jnp.matmul
```

### 2. Native `jax.jit` integration (XLA FFI)

`jaxmetal.ffi.matmul` lowers to an XLA FFI custom call, so it traces and composes
inside `jax.jit` with the rest of your program. (Runs on the CPU backend and copies to
the GPU per call — native *integration*, not yet a native *device*.)

### 3. `device="mps"` — the honest caveat

JAX ops don't take a `device=` kwarg; placement comes from where an array lives plus a
backend device. So `jaxmetal.matmul(device=...)` is an eager convenience wrapper, and
`jaxmetal.ffi.matmul` is the jit-native path. A true `mps` **device**
(`jax.device_put(x, mps)` keeping arrays GPU-resident) is the **PJRT plugin** — see
[`docs/PJRT_PLUGIN.md`](docs/PJRT_PLUGIN.md).

---

## How it fits together

```
JAX  ──►  jaxmetal (Python front-end: device=, batching, jax.jit/FFI)
             │
             ▼
          metalmm  (ctypes binding)
             │
             ▼
   libmetal_capi.dylib  (flat C ABI: matmul / mps / cpu / auto / resident / FFI handler)
             │
             ▼
        metal_rt  (C++/Obj-C++ runtime)
        ├─ ops/matmul       hand-written register-tiled MSL kernel  ("metal")
        ├─ ops/mps_matmul   MPSMatrixMultiplication                 ("mps")
        ├─ cpu/cpu_matmul   Accelerate cblas_sgemm                  ("cpu")
        ├─ ops/elementwise  add/sub/mul/div/max/min, neg/abs/exp
        ├─ metal/…          MTLDevice, MTLBuffer, runtime MSL compile + pipeline cache
        └─ runtime/…        1-D and threadgroup dispatch
```

- **Kernels** (`kernels/*.metal`) are compiled at runtime (`newLibraryWithSource:`) with
  *safe math*, so f32 results match the CPU/JAX bit-for-bit.
- **Two JAX integration paths**: XLA FFI custom call (works today) and a PJRT plugin
  (scaffolded — the native device).

## Repo layout

```
kernels/        hand-written MSL (elementwise, matmul)
src/
  metal/        MetalContext, MetalBuffer, KernelLibrary (runtime MSL compile + cache)
  runtime/      Dispatcher (1-D + threadgroup grids)
  ops/          matmul (MSL), mps_matmul (MPS), elementwise
  cpu/          cpu_matmul (Accelerate)
  capi/         metal_capi — flat C ABI + auto router
  ffi/          metal_ffi — XLA FFI custom-call handler (jax.jit integration)
python/
  jaxmetal/     JAX-facing front-end (matmul device=, batching, .ffi jit path)
  metalmm/      low-level ctypes binding (+ resident DeviceBuffer)
  jax_metal_plugin/  PJRT registration scaffold (Stage 3)
examples/       runnable examples (start here)
benchmarks/     bench_matmul.py — MPS vs hand-kernel vs CPU
tests/cpp/      33 C++ unit tests (per-TEST ctest cases)
docs/           PJRT_PLUGIN.md — the native-device roadmap
CLAUDE.md       full engineering notes / ground truth
```

## Training an MLP on MNIST — on the GPU, faster than CPU

Beyond matmul, the runtime now trains a real neural net. A `784→H→10` MLP (ReLU,
softmax cross-entropy, plain SGD) runs its **entire** forward + backward + weight
update **on the Apple GPU**, with all weights, activations, and gradients kept
**resident** across the SGD loop — the whole step is encoded into a single Metal
command buffer (MPS matmuls + hand-written NN kernels in
[`kernels/nn.metal`](kernels/nn.metal), one commit/one sync).

```bash
.venv/bin/python python/mlp_mnist.py --batch 512 --hidden 1024 --lr 0.5 --epochs 25
```

- **Trains to ~98.1% MNIST test accuracy** (crosses 97% by epoch 5).
- **Faster than the equivalent JAX-CPU `jax.jit` step at batch ≥ 512** — 1.3× at
  B=512, 1.8× at B=1024, **2.7×** at B=2048/H=2048 (~4 TFLOP/s). Below B≈512 the
  ~15 small per-step kernel dispatches dominate and the CPU wins — the same
  residency/scale lesson as the matmul crossover above.
- **Numerically matches a NumPy golden reference** (itself matching `jax.grad` to
  ~1e-8) to ~1e-7 — enforced by a correctness gate before every run.

`python/mlp_mnist.py` runs a correctness gate, a GPU-vs-JAX-CPU benchmark, and the
training loop; the resident MLP lives behind a flat C-ABI (`metal_mlp_*` in
[`src/capi/metal_capi.h`](src/capi/metal_capi.h)) driven from Python via ctypes
([`python/metalmm`](python/metalmm)). This is the Stage-4 *learning* milestone via a
direct resident C-ABI; a real `jax.jit(f, backend='metal')` device is still the PJRT
roadmap ([`docs/PJRT_PLUGIN.md`](docs/PJRT_PLUGIN.md)).

## Status

Working today: hand-written Metal kernels (elementwise + matmul + NN ops), MPS +
Accelerate backends, a JAX front-end with full `jnp.matmul` semantics, **native
`jax.jit` integration via XLA FFI**, and a **resident-GPU MLP that trains MNIST to
~98% faster than JAX-CPU**. In progress: the **PJRT plugin** for a real `mps` device
(`jax.devices("metal")`) — roadmap and scaffold in
[`docs/PJRT_PLUGIN.md`](docs/PJRT_PLUGIN.md).

See [`python/README.md`](python/README.md) for the Python API in depth and
[`CLAUDE.md`](CLAUDE.md) for the full engineering log.
